title: Democratic Visibility Rally
description:

There are two public parking lots on Bridge and River Streets.

title: So You Want to Run for Office – Pride Month Edition: Advance Equality, Run For Office
description:
Everyone should have the right to run – and come to the voter as they are. This Pride Month, join us to explore what it means to run for office if you are an LGBTQ+ leader in the making. 

  

Being out and running for office can feel especially challenging right now. But it’s also why this training can be especially important. Acceptance, representation, a voice at the table, and the protection of our rights all work in tandem. Representation is how we got to a Supreme Court decision about marriage equality. More representation, especially at the grassroots level, is how we will get to have and keep more equality – in all ways – the law of the land. 

  

Are you a member of the LGBTQ+ community and would you like to run for office? Are you perhaps considering a run for elected office but haven’t yet made the commitment to run or filed your candidacy? Then this virtual live training is for you! 

  

Join our expert trainer and come away with insights and next steps on the following topics:

*   Understanding the steps necessary to run for office
    
*   Best practices for choosing which office to run for
    
*   Discerning if running is the right decision for you – especially if you are LGBTQ+ and have never run for office but are thinking about it
    
*   Identifying what kinds of supports you’ll need to run for office
    
*   Preparing for sharing your decision to run with your support network

In honor of Pride Month, NDTC is holding an AMA with LGBTQ+ leaders. Join us for this conversation with courageous leaders on the ground who are advocating for their community’s rights. Find out how they’re fighting back through collective action and crucial elections, and working to elect progressive candidates. 

  

Here’s why this conversation is so important right now: The conservative movement is targeting our schools, our rights, and our voices. Even if elections aren’t happening in your state, hateful bills – more than 575 anti-LGBTQ+ so far in 2025 alone – are still progressing on our watch. Learn how you can take direct action to fight back in your community.

  

You’ll leave this rich conversation with insights into: 

*   Insider Knowledge: Get the “behind the curtain” wisdom on successful electoral strategies and grassroots mobilization.
    
*   Expert Advice: Hear firsthand from seasoned leaders about overcoming challenges and seizing opportunities in today’s political arena.
    
*   Real-Time Answers: Engage directly with our guests and have your questions addressed instantly.
    

  

Have accessibility questions? Reply to your registration email to confirm your requirements or request more information.

title: No Kings Day Mobilization - SAVE THE DATE
description:
WHAT IS “NO KINGS”?

NO KINGS is a national day of action and mass mobilization in response to the increasing authoritarian excesses and corruption of the Trump administration. 

- We’ve watched as they’ve cracked down on free speech, detained people for their political positions, threatened to deport American citizens, and defied the courts. They’ve done this all while continuing to serve and enrich their billionaire allies. They think they rule—but we are bigger than even their worst aspirations.

- Donald Trump is planning a military parade in Washington, D.C. on June 14. This display of might is intended to intimidate opponents and solidify his image as a strongman on our dime—we won’t stand by while that happens.

- Instead of allowing this military parade to be the center of gravity, we will make action everywhere else the story of America that day: people coming together in communities across the country to reject strongman politics and corruption.

- Alongside local organizers, partners, and leaders from across the pro-democracy & pro-worker movement, we will demonstrate organized people power that outpaces any authoritarian aspirations.

* NO KINGS events should be additive and congruent with adjacent mobilizations and recognitions, including Veterans celebrations, Pride events, and Juneteenth on 6/19.

title: NO KINGS Raleigh
description:
This June 14th, stand with us at the steps of the North Carolina State Capitol for No Kings Day—a nonpartisan, peaceful rally in defense of the American principles we all hold dear: democracy, accountability, and the rule of law.

Across the political spectrum, more and more Americans are feeling disillusioned by leaders who put themselves above the people. This day is for anyone who believes that no one—no matter how powerful—should be treated like royalty in a nation built on liberty.

We’re gathering not in anger, but in unity. This is a space for reflection, connection, and a shared commitment to a country where leaders serve, not rule. Whether you're conservative, progressive, independent, or politically unsure—if you believe in the idea of a government by and for the people, this rally is for you.

This is a peaceful, de-escalation-focused event. There is no place here for violence, intimidation, or hate. We welcome calm, respectful voices who want to help shape a future rooted in mutual respect and civic responsibility.

Bring your signs, your friends, your conscience—and your belief that the United States was never meant to have kings.

title: No Kings On D-Day
description:
# On June 6th, 2025, the Anniversary of D-Day, Mass 50501 will hold an event in remembrance of our heroes in uniform, past and present.

Our mission is the preservation of the democracy that they fought—and in some cases died—to protect on the shores of Europe. We will feature speakers who are themselves veterans, who will speak on history, duty, honor, sacrifice, and patriotism. We will conduct a wreath-laying ceremony at the Soldiers and Sailors Monument on the Boston Common featuring patriotic renditions of “Taps,” “Battle Hymn of the Republic,” and other songs. We will protest cuts to the VA, oppose the undemocratic way in which the administration has treated its duties, reaffirm our support for our allies, and recommit ourselves to the principles that have governed the nation and its military for centuries, and we will remind the people that veterans and active duty military personnel exist to protect the nation against all enemies, foreign and domestic. It will be both a protest and a solemn event of remembrance. 

## Event Program

## Act 1: Invocation of Service
An honor guard procession will bear American, State, and Service flags from the Soldiers and Sailors Monument to the stage, followed by an invocation and remarks from the Program Director. 

## Act 2: The Citizen Soldier
We'll hear from ordinary citizens—veterans and those who support them—addressing the issues that matter to veterans today.

## Act 3: A Call to Duty
VIP speakers will offer stories to help draw us together, and remind us that the bonds of service do not end upon separation from the military and that participation in our democracy is essential to its health and prosperity.

## Act 4: Honor the Fallen
The honor guard and key speakers will process back to the Soldiers and Sailors Monument to lay a wreath, followed by Taps, a moment of silence, and closing words. 

# Flags are welcome, but please leave protest signs at home.

title: Rhody Civics Club: Let’s Get Fiscal
description:
Join us for a social speaker series dedicated to learning about Rhode Island government in a friendly, casual environment. Come meet other civic-curious people, and walk away with a tool box of direct actions you can take to make meaningful change in your local community. And maybe make some new friends! 

This event will focus specifically on state, city and town budgets. Expert speakers will present an overview of how a budget is drafted, approved and implemented. They will also discuss specific actions non-elected citizens can take to participate in the process and influence the money that flows back into their communities. Future monthly Rhody Civics Club events will focus on topics such as an overview of the state legislature, how a bill becomes law, housing justice, and how to run an election, among others. 

Small bites will be provided, as well as a full self-pay bar. This event is open to under 21, and the bar will be checking ID. Spend some time chatting with other attendees and building new connections, before transitioning to listening to the expert speakers. There will be a Q&A session at the end. 

All are welcome! Anyone interested in getting more involved in our government is invited. Together we can make democracy what it was always supposed to be: of the people, by the people, for the people.

This event is sponsored by the Rhode Island Working Families Party.

description:
Join us for a vital virtual town hall on Monday, May 12th, at 12 p.m. where we will be joined by Representative Katie Stuart and other special guests. We’ll discuss the fight to defend healthcare access at the federal level, including Medicaid and SNAP, and how Illinois can lead the way with innovative solutions.

title: No Cake for False Kings
description:
🗓️ June 14, 2025
🕐 1:00–4:00 PM
📍 17th Street NW Bridge, over Atlanta highways (near Atlantic Station)

On June 14th, while Donald Trump attempts to display military power meant to silence dissent, we will rise above the noise—literally and symbolically.

No Cake for False Kings is a high-visibility, nonviolent protest that will take place on the 17th Street NW pedestrian bridge, which crosses over ALL of Atlanta’s busiest highways. We are joining activists across America to send one unified message: we reject authoritarianism, abuse of power, and the erasure of our rights.

This is not a celebration. This is a warning.
There will be no cake, no crowns, and no complicity.

🔥 What to Expect:
- A powerful visual presence over the highway with large protest banners

- Protesters lining both sides of the bridge sidewalks to reach drivers below and pedestrians around

- Organized chants, signs, and nonviolent resistance

- An Information & Resource Table with know-your-rights guides, activist materials, and ways to plug in

- A Water & Cooling Station to ensure safety in the heat

** Participants are strongly encouraged to WEAR RED as a unified symbol of protest and defiance. 

🎒What to bring: 
- For those wanting to avoid the summer sun, having an umbrella to provide shade is encouraged. 

- Wear a hat, sunglasses, and sunscreen to protect from the sun!

- Water, water, water! We will have a water station as well as cooling towels and packs, but these are limited, so bring water for yourself and your group if possible.

- Signs and flags are strongly encouraged, but organizers will have extras for those in need *limited, first come first serve 

- Foldable chair: for those needing a break from standing for long periods of time

-Snacks: protesting takes energy, so bring some snacks to refuel! 


🧭 Getting There:
-Parking is available at Atlantic Station just steps away from the bridge

- For those using public transit, MARTA’s Arts Center Station is the closest stop and offers a shuttle to Atlantic Station

This protest is about visibility and truth. We must be loud, proud, and impossible to ignore. Bring your voice, your signs, and your conviction.

Together, we will show this country that we do not bow to tyrants—we rise up against them.
